Simulated Dataset

# load data
load("data_simulated.RData")

This replicable script relies on a simulated sample of 300 (fictive) patients with 10 4-level items measured at repeated visits, and a time to event collected in continuous time.

The data.frame data is in longitudinal format with 1155 rows corresponding to the follow-up visits of the 300 patients, and 15 columns corresponding to the different variables:

  • ID the patient identifier;
  • t the time of study;
  • itemk the value of item k (=1,…,10) with each 4 levels (0 to 3);
  • stage the variable indicating the disease stage with 5 levels (0 to 4);
  • T the time of event or censoring;
  • D the indicator of event or censoring.

Here is an overview of the dataset :

STEP 1: identification of homogeneous sub-scale dimensions

The different dimensions measured by the scale are distinguished using the PROMIS methodology [2]. The PROMIS method aims to ensure the validity of the three calibration assumptions usually required during the statistical analysis:

  • the unidimensionality of the items constituting a dimension,
  • the conditional independence of the items given the underlying construct,
  • the increasing monotonicity of each item.

PROMIS method assesses the assumptions sequentially. However, the authors recommend to make some step-backs at some points to measure the impact of some decisions and to ensure the identified dimensions make clinical sense. PROMIS technique does not handle repeated data so that we performed the first step on all the follow-ups by neglecting the intra-subject correlation.

Unidimensionality

First, an exploratory factorial analysis (EFA) is performed on all the items to identify the different factors (or dimensions) measured by the scale. The optimal number of dimensions is determined according to the scree plot of the successive eigenvalues as the greatest number of factors with successive eigenvalues greater than value 1, or according to the Kaiser criterion [3]. This analysis can be carried out using function fa.parallel() from the R-package psych [4].

# screeplot
screeplot <- fa.parallel(data[,paste("item",1:K,sep="")], fm = 'minres', fa = 'fa', cor='poly')

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  2  and the number of components =  NA

The analysis suggests 2 factors.

Then, each item is assigned to the dimension it contributes the most according to the loadings resulting from an EFA based on the polychoric correlation matrix [3].

# polychoric correlation matrix
pc <- hetcor(data[,paste("item",1:K,sep="")], ML=TRUE)   

# EFA with 2 factors
efa <- fa(r=pc$correlations, nfactors=nfact, rotate="varimax")

tab_contrib_efa <- data.frame(ITEM = paste("item",1:10,sep=""),
                              FACT1 = efa$loadings[,2],
                              FACT2 = efa$loadings[,1])
row.names(tab_contrib_efa) <- 1:K
tab_contrib_efa$CONTRIB_MAX <- apply(tab_contrib_efa[,paste("FACT",1:2,sep="")], 1, max)
tab_contrib_efa$DOMINANT_FACT <- ifelse(tab_contrib_efa$CONTRIB_MAX == tab_contrib_efa$FACT1,1,2)
tab_contrib_efa[,c("ITEM","FACT1","FACT2","DOMINANT_FACT")]

Afterwards, to confirm the previous result and to ensure the sufficient unidimensionality of the identified dimensions (i.e., items from a dimension measure the same phenomenon), a EFA is performed per dimension to control that the number of underlying factors is 1.

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  1  and the number of components =  NA

The analysis concludes to 1 factor (i.e., unidimensionality).

AXIS 2

The analysis concludes to 1 factor (i.e., unidimensionality).

Then, a confirmatory factorial analysis (CFA) is performed to evaluate the model fit based on PROMIS recommended criteria thresholds: comparative fit index (CFI) > 0.95, Tucker Lewis index (TLI) > 0.95, root means square error of approximation (RMSEA) < 0.06, and standardized root mean square residual (SRMR) < 0.08 [2,3]. This analysis can be carried out using function cfa() from the R-package lavaan [5].

# CFA with 2 axes
repartition <- ' AXE1 =~ item1 + item2 + item3 + item4
                 AXE2 =~ item5 + item6 + item7 + item8 + item9 + item10'

cfa <- cfa(repartition, 
           data = data, 
           ordered = paste("item",1:K,sep=""))

Local independence

To ensure the conditional independence (i.e., items from the same dimension do not carry redundant information), the residual correlation matrix between the CFA fitted values and the observed items values of each dimension is computed. PROMIS authors consider that the assumption is not satisfied for a residual correlation greater than 0.2 between two items, and recommend, in the case, to remove one of them.

N_cov <- list(
  observed=inspect(cfa, 'sampstat')$cov,
  fitted=fitted(cfa)$cov
)

N_cor <- list(
  observed=cov2cor(N_cov$observed),
  fitted=cov2cor(N_cov$fitted)
)

N_cor$residuals <- N_cor$observed - N_cor$fitted

N_cor <- lapply(N_cor, function(X) round(X, 2))

N_cor$residuals

Increasing monotonicity

To ensure the increasing monotonocity (i.e., higher levels of items always correspond to higher levels of impairment), a non-parametric IRT model is run for each dimension using function check.monotonicity() from R-package mokken [6]. It permits to compute the probabilities of endorsing a higher level for each item and to predict the item level to be compared to the increasing dimension sumscores (excepting the considered item score) through plots. According to the authors, the item response curves should be increasing, or, at least, constant.

AXIS 1

check.mono.axe1 <- check.monotonicity(data[,paste("item",1:4,sep="")], minsize=100)

At this stage, each homogenous sub-scale is identified and can be analyzed separately in steps 2 to 4.

In this script, steps 2 to 4 are illustrated below on AXE 1 only.

STEP 2: description of items’ trajectories over time and associated factors

The trajectory of each dimension continuum was modeled over time from the repeated item data using a joint Item Response Theory (IRT) model adapted to ordinal repeated measures and time-to-event data [7]. The model is composed of a longitudinal submodel and a survival submodel simultaneously estimated by maximum likelihood in the R-package JLPM (available on CRAN [8] and https://github.com/VivianePhilipps/JLPM).

The longitudinal submodel combines:

  1. a linear mixed structural model to describe the underlying dimension deterioration over time according to covariates and functions of time, the fixed effects defining the mean dimension trajectory at the population level and individual correlated random effects capturing individual deviations;

  2. an item-specific cumulative probit measurement model to define the link between the underlying dimension and each item observation.

The survival submodel is a proportional hazard survival model adjusted on the current underlying dimension level as a linear predictor to account for the informative dropout induced by deaths. For further details, please refer to Saulnier et al. [7].

Estimation

# (optional) initial values
B <- c(0.4472136,2.2360680,0.1, #survival submodel
       1, #fixed effects
       0,0.2, #random effects
       0,1.7320508,1.4142136, #item thresholds
       -1,1.7320508,1.4142136,
       0.5,1.4142136,1.7320508,
       2,1.4142136,1.4142136,
       1,1,1,1) #measurement errors

# model estimation
M_AXE1 <- jointLPM(fixed = item1 + item2 + item3 + item4 ~ t,
                   random = ~ 1 + t,
                   survival = Surv(T, D) ~ 1,
                   sharedtype = "CL",
                   var.time = "t",
                   subject = "ID",
                   data = data,
                   link = "thresholds",
                   methInteg = "QMC",
                   B = B,
                   nMC = 1000,
                   nproc = 5)
summary(M_AXE1)

Graph representing items’ degradation hierarchy

nl <- 4 #nb of level per item

STEP 3: mapping of item impairment hierarchy to disease stages

The disease stages are projected onto a dimension continuum using a joint bivariate model to link the disease stages to the dimension total sumscore. This can be performed using the R-package JLPM [8], also adapted to treat continuous markers by replacing the cumulative probit measurement models by linear and curvilinear measurement models (the curvilinear model involves a parameterized bijective link function approximated by splines which captures the departure from normality of the variable) [7]. Then, thresholds in the dimension continuum corresponding to each disease stage can be deduced by predicting the dimension sumscores that correspond to a change of disease stage and expressing them in the dimension process scale. Note that, as this part requires the computation of dimension sumscores, it doesn’t handled missing data.

Model with stage variable/outcome

# score variable

       1,1) #measurement errors

################################################################################
# function
threshold_in_latent_scale <- function(thres.stg,data,B.stg_multlcmm,ni,nl,thres.item,discrim.item){
  
  #####
  ### predict the score of the axe corresponding to stagechanges
  #####
  
  M.stg_multlcmm <- multlcmm(fixed = score_AXE1 ~ t,
                             random = ~ t,
                             subject = "ID", 
                             data = data, 
                             link = "3-quant-splines",
                             methInteg = "QMC", 
                             nMC = 1000,
                             B = B.stg_multlcmm,
                             maxiter = 0,
                             verbose = FALSE)
  Y_thres.stg <- predictYcond(x = M.stg_multlcmm,lprocess = thres.stg,nsim=500)$pred$Ypred
  
  #####
  ### conditional expectancy to deduct thresholds in the latent scale of the axe
  #####
  
  # compute pultiple values of the latent scale
  tmp <- data.frame(lambda = seq(from = -10, to = 10, by = 0.001))
  tmp$sum <- sapply(X = tmp$lambda, FUN = expect, ni=ni, nl=nl, discrim = discrim.item, thres = thres.item)
  
  # lambda as score == sum of items
  res <- rep(NA,length(thres.stg))
  for(j in 1:length(thres.stg))
    res[j] <- tmp$lambda[which(abs(tmp$sum - Y_thres.stg[j]) == min(abs(tmp$sum - Y_thres.stg[j])))]
  res
  
  return(res)
}

# sub-function of the conditional expectancy: E[sum(Y)] = sum_k{nl - sum(P(Yk<=m))_m=0,...,nl-1}
expect <- function(lambda, ni, nl, discrim, thres){
  
  proba <- matrix(NA,nrow=nl-1,ncol=ni) # matrix of probas P(Y<=m) with m=0,1,2,..,(nl-2)
  for(k in 1:ni)
    for(l in 1:(nl-1))
      proba[l,k] <- pnorm(-discrim[k]*(lambda-thres[l,k]))
  
  probaSum <- colSums(proba)
  probaSum <- sum(probaSum)
  
  res <- ni*(nl-1) - probaSum
  
  return(res)
}

STEP 4: Most informative items by disease stage

The contribution of each item can be quantified by the percentage of information it carries at each stage. The information is defined by the Fisher Information function (i.e., the second derivative of the item probability with respect to the underlying dimension) which is integrated over all the underlying dimension values corresponding to a specific stage (as determined in Step 3) to obtain the item-and-stage-specific information. The total information of a dimension at a specific stage is then the sum of all the item-and-stage-specific informations so that the percentage of total information carried by an item at a disease stage can be easily deduced.

Fisher information table

### FISHER INFORMATION COMUTATION

################################################################################
# function to compute the Fisher information carried by items during stages
fisher_information <- function(thres,discrim,ni,nl,ns,lambda.s){
  
  ### info brut
  info <- matrix(NA, ncol = ns, nrow = ni)
  
  for(i in 1:ni){ # item i
    
    for(s in 1:ns){ # stage s
      
      ##boundaries of stage s
      if(s == 1){ # first stage
        lambda.s.inf <- -Inf
        lambda.s.sup <- lambda.s[1]
      }
      if(s == ns){ # last stage
        lambda.s.inf <- lambda.s[ns-1]
        lambda.s.sup <- +Inf
      }
      if(s != 1 && s != ns){ # other stages
        lambda.s.inf <- lambda.s[s-1]
        lambda.s.sup <- lambda.s[s]
      }
      
      E1 <- 0 #first element = sum_i(integral)
      E2 <- 0 # second element = sum_i(subtraction)
      for(m in 0:(nl-1)){ # level m
        E1 <- E1 + integrate(f=fct_to_integrate,lower=lambda.s.inf,upper=lambda.s.sup,i,thres,discrim,m,nl)$value
        E2 <- E2 + Pim.prime(lambda=lambda.s.sup,i,thres,discrim,m,nl) - Pim.prime(lambda=lambda.s.inf,i,thres,discrim,m,nl)
      }  
      
      info[i,s] <- E1 - E2
      
    }
    
  }
  
  ### info in %
  percent <- info
  for(i in 1:ni)
    percent[i,] <- percent[i,] / colSums(info)
  percent <- percent * 100
  colSums(percent) # verif == 100 ?
  
 res <- list(info,percent)
 
 return(res)
  
}

#####
### function proba P : Pim(lambda) = P(Yi = m |lambda)
#####
Pim <- function(lambda,
                i,thres,discrim,
                m,nl){
  
  res <- NA
  
  discrim_i <- discrim[i]
  
  # m=0, smaller level
  if(m == 0){
    thres.im <- thres[1,i]
    res <- pnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im))
  }
  
  # m=nl-1, higher level
  if(m == (nl-1)){
    thres.im <- thres[nl-1,i]
    res <- 1 - pnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im))
  }
  
  # other levels
  if(m != 0 && m!=(nl-1)){
    thres.im.inf <- thres[m,i]
    thres.im.sup <- thres[m+1,i]
    res <- pnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im.sup)) - pnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im.inf))
  }
  
  return(res)  
  
}

#####
### function first derive P' : P'im(lambda) = dPim(lambda) / dlambda
#####
Pim.prime <- function(lambda,
                      i,thres,discrim,
                      m,nl){
  
  res <- NA
  
  discrim_i <- discrim[i]
  
  # m=0, smaller level
  if(m == 0){
    thres.im <- thres[1,i]
    res <- -discrim_i * dnorm(-discrim_i*(lambda - thres.im))
  }
  
  # m=nl-1, higher level
  if(m == (nl-1)){
    thres.im <- thres[nl-1,i]
    res <- discrim_i * dnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im))
  }
  
  # other levels
  if(m != 0 && m!=(nl-1)){
    thres.im.inf <- thres[m,i]
    thres.im.sup <- thres[m+1,i]
    res <- -discrim_i * dnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im.sup)) + discrim_i * dnorm(-discrim_i * (lambda - thres.im.inf))
  }
  
  return(res)  
  
}

#####
### function to integrate : (P'im)^2 / Pim between boundaries corresponding to stage s
#####
fct_to_integrate <- function(lambda,
                             i,thres,discrim,
                             m,nl){

  res <- Pim.prime(lambda,i,thres,discrim,m,nl)^2
  denom <- Pim(lambda,i,thres,discrim,m,nl)
  res <- ifelse(denom == 0,
                res <- 0,
                res <- res / denom)
  return(res)
  
}
################################################################################
